<subsection> 
<title>Combining Like Terms </title>

<p>When we take <m>2a+3a</m> and write this as <m>5a</m> we <term>combine like terms</term>. The formal process actually involves invoking the distributive property, as we obtain:
<md>
    <mrow>2a+3a \amp=(2+3)a    </mrow>
    <mrow>\amp=5a</mrow>
</md>
In practice, it's helpful to think of this as having <m>2</m> of an object and then an additional <m>3</m> of that same object. In total, we then have <m>5</m> of that object.</p>

<example>
    <statement>
        <p>Where possible, simplify the following expressions by combining like terms.
        <ol>
            <li><p><m>6c+12c-5c</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>-5q-3q</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>-3x-5y+4x</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>2x-3y+4z</m></p></li>
        </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p><ol>
            <li><p><md>
                <mrow>6c+12c-5c \amp=18c-5c</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=13c</mrow>
            </md></p></li>
            <li><p><md>
                <mrow>-5q-3q \amp=-8q</mrow>
            </md></p></li>
            <li><p><md>
                <mrow>-3x-5y+4x \amp=-3x+4x+(-5y)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=x-5y</mrow>
            </md></p></li>
            <li><p>The expression <m>2x-3y+4z</m> cannot be simplified as there are no like terms.
            </p></li>
        </ol></p>
    </solution>
</example>

<remark><p>The expression <m>x</m> represents <m>1x</m>, but we don't write the <q><m>1</m></q> as it's implied. However, it's helpful when combining like terms to remember that <m>x=1x</m>.</p></remark>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Adding Expressions</title>

<p>When we add an expression like <m>4x-5</m> to an expression like <m>3x-7</m>, we write the expression as follows:
<me>(4x-5)+(3x-7)</me>
In order to remove the given sets of parentheses and combine like terms, one helpful approach is to write every term using addition, as follows:
<me>4x+(-5)+3x+(-7)</me>
Now that we're at this point, we can apply the commutative property of addition and then combine like terms. Here's how the entire problem will look:
<md>
    <mrow>(4x-5)+(3x-7)\amp=4x+(-5)+3x+(-7)</mrow>
    <mrow>\amp=4x+3x+(-5)+(-7)</mrow>
    <mrow>\amp=7x+(-12)</mrow>
    <mrow>\amp=7x-12</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<remark>Once we get more comfortable simplifying such expressions, your work will look more like this:
<me>(4x-5)+(3x-7)=7x-12</me>
</remark>

<example>
    <statement>
        <p>Use the associative, commutative, and distributive properties to simplify the following expressions as much as possible.
        <ol>
            <li><p><m>(2x+3)+(4x+5)</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>(-5x+3)+(4x-7)</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>(-2x-1)+(-4x-9)</m></p></li>
        </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p><ol>
            <li><p><md>
                <mrow>(2x+3)+(4x+5) \amp=2x+3+4x+5</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=2x+4x+3+5</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=6x+8</mrow>
            </md></p></li>
            <li><p><md>
                <mrow>(-5x+3)+(4x-7)\amp=-5x+3+4x+(-7)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=7x+(-4)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=7x-4</mrow>
            </md></p></li>
            <li><p><md>
                <mrow>(-2x-1)+(-4x-9) \amp=-2x+(-1)+(-4x)+(-9)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-2x+(-4x)+(-1)+(-9)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-6x+(-10)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-6x-10</mrow>
            </md></p></li>
        </ol></p>
    </solution>
</example>
</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Applying the Distributive Property with Negative Coefficients</title>

<p>Applying the distributive property in an expression such as <m>2(3x+4)</m> is fairly straightforward, in that this becomes <m>2(3x)+2(4)</m> which we then simplify to <m>6x+8</m>. Applying the distributive property is a little trickier when subtraction or a negative constant is involved, for example with the expression <m>2(3x-4)</m>. Recalling that subtraction is defined as <q>adding the opposite</q>, we can change the subtraction of positive <m>4</m> to the addition of negative <m>4</m>:
<me>2(3x+(-4))</me>
Now when we distribute, we obtain:
<me>2(3x)+2(-4)</me>
As a final step, we see that this simplifies to:
<me>6x-8</me>
</p>

<remark><p>We can also create a secondary distributive property involving subtraction, which states that <m>a(b-c)=ab-ac</m>. With this property, we would simplify <m>2(3x-4)</m> more efficiently:
<md>
    <mrow>2(3x-4) \amp=2(3x)-2(4)</mrow>
    <mrow>\amp=6x-8</mrow>
</md>
</p></remark>

<example>
    <statement>
        <p>Apply the distributive property to each expression and simplify it as much as possible.
        <ol>
            <li><p><m>-3(5x+7)</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>2(-4x-1)</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>-4(2x-3)</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>-7(-x-9)</m></p></li>
        </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p><ol>
            <li><p><md>
                <mrow>-3(5x+7)\amp=-3(5x)+(-3)(7)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-15x+(-21)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-15x-21</mrow>
            </md></p></li>
            <li><p><md>
                <mrow>2(-4x-1)\amp=2(-4x+(-1))</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=2(-4x)+2(-1)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-8x+(-2)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-8x-2</mrow>
            </md></p></li>
            <li><p><md>
                <mrow>-4(2x-3)\amp=-4(2x+(-3)) </mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-4(2x)+(-4)(-3)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-8x+12</mrow>
            </md></p></li>
            <li><p><md>
                <mrow>-7(-x-9)\amp=-7(-x+(-9)) </mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-7(-x)+(-7)(-9)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=7x+63</mrow>
            </md></p></li>
        </ol></p>
    </solution>
</example>

