<subsection>
<title>Subtracting Expressions</title>

<p>To subtract one expression from another expression, such as <m>(5x+9)-(3x+2)</m>, we will again rely on the fact that subtraction is defined as <q>adding the opposite</q>. To add the <em>opposite</em> of an expression, we'll distribute a constant factor of <m>-1</m> and simplify from there:
<md>
    <mrow>(5x+9)-(3x+2)\amp=(5x+9)+(-1)(3x+2)</mrow>
    <mrow>\amp=5x+9+(-1)(3x)+(-1)(2)</mrow>
    <mrow>\amp=5x+9+(-3x)+(-2)</mrow>
    <mrow>\amp=6x+7</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<remark><p>Once we get more comfortable simplifying such expressions, your work will look more like this:
<md>
    <mrow>(5x+9)-(3x+2)\amp=5x+9-3x-2</mrow>
    <mrow>\amp=6x+7</mrow>
</md>
</p></remark>

<example>
    <statement>
        <p>Use the associative, commutative, and distributive properties to simplify the following expressions as much as possible.
        <ol>
            <li><p><m>(-6x+4)-(3x-7)</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>(-2x-5)-(-4x-6)</m></p></li>
        </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p><ol>
            <li><p><md>
                <mrow>(-6x+4)-(3x-7) \amp=(-6x+4)+(-1)(3x+(-7))</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-6x+4+(-1)(3x)+(-1)(-7)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-6x+4+(-3x)+7</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-9x+11</mrow>
            </md></p></li>
            <li><p><md>
                <mrow>(-2x-5)-(-4x-6)\amp=(-2x+(-5))+(-1)(-4x+(-6))</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-2x+(-5)+(-1)(-4x)+(-1)(-6)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-2x+(-5)+4x+6</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=2x+1</mrow>
            </md></p></li>
        </ol></p>
    </solution>
</example>


</subsection>


<subsection> 
<title>Examples Using the Commutative, Associative, and Distributive Properties</title>
</subsection>

<p>When simplifying an expression such as <m>3+4(5x+7)</m>, we will need to use each of the commutative, associative, and distributive properties. In order to know where to start, we will rely on the order of operations. Noting that the expression inside parentheses, <m>5x+7</m> is already simplified and we do not have exponents, the first thing we will do is to multiply. This means that we will first apply the distributive property. After that, we will use the associative and commutative properties in order to finish simplifying the expression:
<md>
    <mrow>3+4(5x+7)\amp=3+4(5x)+4(7)</mrow>
    <mrow>\amp=3+20x+28</mrow>
    <mrow>\amp=20x+31</mrow>
</md>

