<subsection> 
<title>Introduction to the Rules of Exponents</title>

<p>So far, we have added and subtracted expressions like <m>5x^2</m> and <m>x^2</m>. We discovered that these could only be added or subtracted if the two expressions were like terms. In this section, we're going to look at what happens when we multiply two such expressions and what happens when we raise one such expression to an exponent. One key thing to note is that we don't need like terms in order to do this.</p>

<example>
    <statement>
        <p><ol>
            <li><p>Let's look at what happens when we try to simplify <m>x^2x^3</m>. If we write this out entirely with <m>x</m>, we have 
            <md>
                <mrow>x^2\cdot x^3 \amp=(x\cdot x)(x \cdot x \cdot x)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=x\cdot x\cdot x \cdot x \cdot x</mrow>        
                <mrow>\amp=x^5</mrow>        
            </md>
            Note that to determine how many times <m>x</m> appeared as a factor (simply by counting this out), we see that we obtained the exponent of <m>5</m> by adding <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>.
            </p></li>
            <li><p>Let's look at what happens when we try to simplify <m>\left(x^2\right)^3</m>. If we write this out entirely with <m>x</m>, we have 
            <md>
                <mrow>\left(x^2\right)^3 \amp=\left(x^2\right)\left(x^2\right)\left(x^2\right)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=(x\cdot x)(x \cdot x) (x \cdot x)</mrow>        
                <mrow>\amp=x\cdot x \cdot x \cdot x \cdot x \cdot x</mrow>        
                <mrow>\amp=x^6</mrow>        
            </md>
            Note that to determine how many times <m>x</m> appeared as a factor (simply by multiplying this out), we see that we obtained the exponent of <m>6</m> by multiplying <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>.
            </p></li>
            <li><p>Let's look at what happens when we try to simplify <m>(xy)^2</m>. If we write this out entirely with <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, we have 
            <md>
                <mrow>(xy)^2 \amp=(xy)(xy)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=x \cdot y \cdot x \cdot y</mrow>        
                <mrow>\amp=x \cdot x \cdot y \cdot y</mrow>        
                <mrow>\amp=x^2y^2</mrow>        
            </md>
            Note that to determine how many times <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> appear as a factors (simply by counting this out and rearranging), the exponent on <m>xy</m> can simply be applied to both <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
            </p></li>
        </ol></p>
    </statement>
</example>
</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Summary of the Rules of Exponents</title>

<ol xml:id="list-rules-of-exponents">
    <li xml:id="item-product-to-sum-exponent-rule"><p><m>x^m\cdot x^n=x^{m+n}</m></p></li>
    <li xml:id="item-exponent-on-an-exponent-rule"><p><m>(x^m)^n=x^{m\cdot n}</m></p></li>
    <li xml:id="item-exponent-on-a-product-rule"><p><m>(xy)^n = x^n\cdot y^n</m></p></li>
</ol>    

