<subsection>
<title>Examples Using the Rules of Exponents</title>

<example>
    <statement>
        <p>Simplify the following expressions using the rules of exponents.
        <ol>
            <li><p><m>-2t^3\cdot 4t^5</m></p></li>            
            <li><p><m>5\left(v^4\right)^2</m></p></li>                    
            <li><p><m>4(3u)^2</m></p></li>                    
        </ol></p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p><ol>
            <li><p>To simplify <m>-2t^3\cdot 4t^5</m>, we want to multiply and simplify the constant factors and then apply the <xref ref="item-product-to-sum-exponent-rule">exponent rule</xref>:
            <md> 
                <mrow>-2t^3\cdot 4t^5 \amp=-2\cdot 4 \cdot t^3\cdot t^5</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-8t^{3+5}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=-8t^8</mrow>
            </md></p></li>                    
            <li><p>To start simplifying <m>5\left(v^4\right)^2</m>, we want to first identify that the factor of <m>5</m> is <em>outside</em> the parentheses to which the exponent of <m>2</m> applies. According to the order of operations, this means that we will first apply the exponent and then multiply. In applying this exponent, we'll use <xref ref="item-exponent-on-an-exponent-rule">exponent rule</xref>:
            <md> 
                <mrow>5\left(v^4\right)^2 \amp=5\left(v^{4\cdot 2}\right)</mrow>
                <mrow>5v^8</mrow>
            </md></p></li>                    
            <li><p>As we simplify <m>4(3u)^2</m>, we will again note that the exponent of <m>2</m> only applies to part of the expression. This means that we will first simplify <m>(3u)^2</m> according to the <xref ref="item-exponent-on-an-exponent-rule">exponent rule</xref>:
            <md> 
                <mrow>4(3u)^2</mrow>
                <mrow>4\left(3^2\cdot u^2\right)</mrow>
                <mrow>4\left(9u^2\right)</mrow>
                <mrow>36u^2</mrow>
            </md></p></li>                    
        </ol></p>
    </solution>
</example>

<remark><p>We cannot simplify an expression like <m>x^2y^3</m> using the rules of exponents. If we tried to apply <xref ref="item-product-to-sum-exponent-rule">exponent rule</xref>, we'd get stuck as the two terms do not have the same b
ase. (One has <m>x</m> as a base and the other has <m>y</m>). If we tried to apply  <xref ref="item-exponent-on-an-exponent-rule">exponent rule</xref>, we'd get stuck as the exponents on each are not the same. (One has an exponent of <m>2</m> whereas the other has an exponent of <m>3</m>.)</p></remark>
</subsection>

<example>
    <statement>
        <p>Simplify the following expressions using the rules of exponents and the distributive property.
        <ol>
            <li><p><m>2x(3x+4)</m></p></li>            
            <li><p><m>3x^2(5x-2)</m></p></li>            
        </ol></p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p><ol>
            <li><p>To simplify <m>2x(3x+4)</m>, we want to first distribute <m>2x</m>, and then we can apply the <xref ref="item-product-to-sum-exponent-rule">exponent rule</xref>:
            <md> 
                <mrow>2x(3x+4)\amp=2x(3x)+2x(4)</mrow>
                <mrow>6x^2+8x</mrow>
            </md></p></li>                    
            <li><p>To start simplifying <m>5\left(v^4\right)^2</m>, we want to first identify that the factor of <m>5</m> is <em>outside</em> the parentheses to which the exponent of <m>2</m> applies. According to the order of operations, this means that we will first apply the exponent and then multiply. In applying this exponent, we'll use <xref ref="item-exponent-on-an-exponent-rule">exponent rule</xref>:
            <md> 
                <mrow>3x^2(5x-2)\amp=3x^2(5x)-3x^2(2)</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=15x^3-6x^2</mrow>
            </md></p></li>                    
        </ol></p>
    </solution>
</example>
</section>
